Observation Details: Displaying Tom and 2 females.  Based primarily upon range we think these are the Rio Grande subspecie of WITU, Meleagris gallopavo intermedia. According to 'Owlcation.com',  there are 5 subspecies of WITU. The Rio Grande subspecie is native to the central plains states and so the common name is for the area in which it is found, Texas, Oklahoma, Kansas, and Northeastern Mexico.  They were first described by George B Sennett in 1879, and he described them as "intermediate" in appearance between the eastern and western subspecies, hence their scientific name.

I hear a thump thump THUMP coming up behind me on the bike path and turn, expecting a large dog or perhaps a bear, only to see a big turkey galloping down the front bike lane straight at me. He stopped about 10 feet away and stared at me, flapped his wings a lot, I took pics and kept going. He starts galloping after me again. I’m afraid now. A biker stops, a jogger passes, but that turkey is fixated on me. He pursued me three more times at full gallop, always stopping about 5 feet away. Finally I held a stick toward him and told him to back off and he got the message. I hope he’s doing ok

Observation Details: Displaying Tom and 2 females.  Based primarily upon range we think these are the Rio Grande subspecie of WITU, Meleagris gallopavo intermedia. According to 'Owlcation.com',  there are 5 subspecies of WITU. The Rio Grande subspecie is native to the central plains states and so the common name is for the area in which it is found, Texas, Oklahoma, Kansas, and Northeastern Mexico.  They were first described by George B Sennett in 1879, and he described them as "intermediate" in appearance between the eastern and western subspecies, hence their scientific name.

Media notes: Male resting peacefully on our deck; snood partially extended, with hair-like feathers on the tip. Not in view, this male is two feet from our sleeping cat. This turkey slept here for hours. When the ground is wet, the wild turkeys like to come onto our wooden deck or shingled roof and snooze. This turkey is also known as a "Rio Grande" or a "Southwestern" turkey. Elevation: 134 m. Date added to IBC: June 21, 2016.

Male in full display with full extension of feathers, wattle and snood. Also known as "Rio Grande" or "Southwestern" wild turkey. Note blue color of face, red wattle and snood and white tips on tail and uppertail coverts; this male had just chased me through my garden and was angry. The more aggitated they are, the bluer their head is. Also note the unusual straight feathers coming from the center of the chest and extending outward, generally size of this "necktie" is a marker for age on males. Elevation: 222 m. Date added to IBC: June 21, 2016.

Locality: 3129 West Snoqualmie River Road Northeast, Carnation, Washington, US (47.636, -121.933)
Observation Details: Provenance questionable but reporting in case others are interested. This location is approximately 60 km from established population in Kittitas, though there are some closer records along the I-90 corridor, including one eBird record from Rattlesnake Lake. "Birding in Seattle and King County" by E.S. Hunn mentions possibility that birds along I-90 near Snoqualmie Pass may be derived from birds introduced around Cle Elum, though occurrence elsewhere in King County said likely to be "barnyard strays". Bird appears to be Merriam's subspecies, same as occurs in Kittitas.  (Eastern subspecies has been introduced to SW WA; Rio Grande subspecies in SE WA.)  Presumably same individual seen on Nov. 15 (http://ebird.org/checklist/S76287178) and Dec. 13 (http://eBird.org/checklist/S77449408); pattern of caruncles above left eye and top of head as well as pattern on inner secondaries of left wing appear to match photos from Nov. 15. Face appears to have more blue on both previous observations, but color may have been washed out from headlights of my vehicle.   Perhaps coincidentally, all observations have been on Sundays, maybe due to less traffic on road, or maybe its owner let's it out for a walk then.  Checklist location is where it was first spotted. It then walked north into a yard on the west side of road as I approached, but it did not seem to be overly wary.

This large flock was in the yard across the street, and was made up mostly of very large adult males. They had colorful blue and red heads, and prominent wattles, snoods, and beards. All the turkeys were chasing each other, sparring, and constantly clucking and gobbling. They were very noisy up close! Most of the birds were dark in color, with iridescent feathers on their upper wings, and white tails and primaries. A few of the males were mostly white with brown and tan feathers scattered throughout. They continued this spectacle for about ten minutes before leaving.

Two toms fighting. Watched at a respectful distance for 30 minutes. It seemed to me that this battle was some sort of neck wrestling. From the moment I spotted them, their beaks were interlocked until the end when the presumed loser let go. In my view, the goal of the bout was to twist your opponent's neck until it became unbearable. The dominant tom appeared slightly larger. At the end of the fight, the loser slinked away slowly. Photos in chronological order.

Media notes: Small beard

Most male turkeys have beards. A beard is a collection of filaments that grows from the breast of a male turkey1. It begins growing when a turkey is about 5 months old and continues to grow throughout his life. A beard can help determine the age of a male turkey. A turkey can have more than one beard. Some even have up to four.

Media notes: This photo shows the changes in appearance that take place when a male is displaying for the females.  The colors of the skin on the face, head, snood and waddle become more intense.  The shape of the snood and waddle elongate and expand, and the the feathers of the body, tail, and wing are raised or splayed.  Very dramatic.  At times he also appeared to be engaged in a short but  "orchestrated dance" with a particular order of dance steps.
Observation Details: Displaying Tom and 2 females.  Based primarily upon range we think these are the Rio Grande subspecie of WITU, Meleagris gallopavo intermedia. According to 'Owlcation.com',  there are 5 subspecies of WITU. The Rio Grande subspecie is native to the central plains states and so the common name is for the area in which it is found, Texas, Oklahoma, Kansas, and Northeastern Mexico.  They were first described by George B Sennett in 1879, and he described them as "intermediate" in appearance between the eastern and western subspecies, hence their scientific name.

Media notes: Left bird has beard; right bird is beardless.
Observation Details: The same 2 toms that showed up at the fountain feeding station last night were here again this morning. They appear to be the same--large--size, but one has an 8-9-inch-long beard, and the other lacks any beard whatsoever.  A mature tom turkey without a beard in Whitetail Canyon is very rare. Generally the 2 stayed within 10-15 feet of one another, but the bearded tom did seem dominant.  First bird heard today was a tom gobbling just before daylight.  This afternoon about 5 p.m. I heard footsteps on the deck outside the office/ guest-house and saw a few hen turkeys.  There actually were at least 9 hens and/or immature males--absent for the past 2 weeks.  Wiretap, the hen with the defunct radio transmitter, was among them. All were dwarfed by the 2 adult toms.  This evening at 6:45 p.m. I saw 3 hens fly from the big sycamore at the ford and roost in the sycamore over our roof. In low light about 7 p.m. I counted at least 9 turkeys roosting in the big sycamore at the ford.

Observation Details: The first gobbler of spring showed up in mid-morning.  When the 6 hens returned at 7:30 am after departing up canyon as usual at 6:50, I suspected a predator.  It was probably the tom.  They left again at 8:30.  The male arrived in the yard around 10 am and immediately went to the fountain feeding station, implying previous familiarity with our property.  Since there were no hens, it began fighting its own reflection in the garage window.  It does not appear to be a particularly large male.  I suspect it is only in its 1st or 2nd spring after hatching.

His brother or friend that was always by his side has stayed next to his body, frequently examining it visually. Quite sad. Looking at my photos of him, his nostrils appear to be clogged. I hope this is not avian flu recently being seen in wild turkeys.

Locality: Choke Canyon State Park, Calliham US-TX 28.48937, -98.34046
Observation Details: Displaying Tom and 2 females.  Based primarily upon range we think these are the Rio Grande subspecie of WITU, Meleagris gallopavo intermedia. According to 'Owlcation.com',  there are 5 subspecies of WITU. The Rio Grande subspecie is native to the central plains states and so the common name is for the area in which it is found, Texas, Oklahoma, Kansas, and Northeastern Mexico.  They were first described by George B Sennett in 1879, and he described them as "intermediate" in appearance between the eastern and western subspecies, hence their scientific name.

Media notes: Wild Turkey - stuff is getting real
Observation Details: We watched two of the wild turkeys sparring with each other for a minute or so; we thought they were done, when they started up again.  It was clear that the largest tom was the reigning champ - before, during and after the event!  The dominant turkey kept his opponent down most of the time.  It was really interesting to watch dominance being established.  We've included some photos to show some of the sequence of this block-buster fight!

Observation Details: Calmly working the ground under the trees near the Supt's residence. They were not spooked by cars and I wondered if they were domesticated escapees. These had the characteristics of the Merriam's Turkey subspecies, M. gallopavo merriami, but I cannot definitively claim this. I am aware that some authorities maintain that this subspecies does not extend into Oklahoma and that turkeys with whitish tail tips and tail coverts are intergrades between the Merriam's and Rio Grande subspecies.

Locality: Midtown East, 42nd-59th St.; E River-5th Ave.
Observation Details: Huge galliform bird hanging out in two small raised planters on East 49th Street during peak evening rush hour, clotting the flow of pedestrian traffic as people stopped to gawk and take pictures. The bird's bronzy-brown plumage with dark barring easily ruled out other land fowl that could conceivably turn up as exotic escapees in New York, like peafowl, guineafowl, or pheasants. The bird's brown-fringed breast feathers, lack of a "beard" on the breast, and lack of spurs on the tarsi indicate that it is a female, and the uneven lengths of the rectrices (central rectrices longer and lateral rectrices significantly shorter) indicate that this is a first cycle/SY bird, i.e., a bird hatched last spring (reference: Peter Pyle's Identification Guide to North American Birds). The lack of white plumage and the sleek body shape seem to indicate that this is a wild-type bird, not a domestic bird.  I went looking for this bird because earlier in the afternoon, I had seen a cell phone photo of a Wild Turkey posted to iNaturalist by someone visiting from out of state. That seemed worth checking out after work, and indeed it was.  The bird certainly looked like a fish out of water, but it was calm and was tolerating close approaches by onlookers (of course, people should give the bird a wide berth for its sake and theirs) and drinking from a container of water put out by nearby restaurant staff. It did not like loud noises, however, and it came to attention for sirens, bangs, etc. Its path to happier environs seems like a challenging one. Some folks did make calls trying to assess assistance options. Evidently non-birders had been posting about the bird on social media through the day, including videos of the bird walking in the street.  Photos attached.

She was walking up the neighbor's driveway and foraging in the edges of garden beds and yards. She paused next to the neighbor's car and appeared to be watching her reflection in the side of the car for a moment or two -- maybe she thought her reflection was another turkey? -- and then she walked on up the backyards and around various neighbor fences. We walked around the block trying to find her again and discovered that neighbors along the street behind us had seen her when she crossed there, and told us she went on through the neighborhood. The neighbor across the street from us said that before he retired about five years ago, when he would walk out the door at 4 AM to go to work, he would sometimes see a small flock of turkeys on our street! Not sure where they hang out when they're not wandering the neighborhood. This hand appeared to be by herself this afternoon.

Observation Details: I  had crossed the far side of the dam and was near the road, when suddenly, 2 large black birds with naked heads swooped down  toward me. As they got closer, I saw that they were turkeys flying like turkey vultures! One majestically glided over the ravine and proceeded to call repeatedly when it landed. The other made a loud crash landing on the path goes downhill. Two turkeys were waiting for their clumsier pal. After a bit of quiet gobbling, those 3 turkeys gracefully flew over to join the 1st turkey, who then stopped calling. It was quite an experience!

Two toms fighting. Watched at a respectful distance for 30 minutes. It seemed to me that this battle was some sort of neck wrestling. From the moment I spotted them, their beaks were interlocked until the end when the presumed loser let go. In my view, the goal of the bout was to twist your opponent's neck until it became unbearable. The dominant tom appeared slightly larger. At the end of the fight, the loser slinked away slowly. Photos in chronological order.

Interesting that I found the four Male WITU on the south side and rest ( females and young) were on the north side of the road. The Males were very accommodating but when I drove over to the north side of the road to see this large flock, the flock immediately scattered to the nearby forest. I grabbed my camera and snapped a few photos of the female WITU running fast. The young were a head of them. Very unfortunately I did not get a picture of the young juveniles to get an accurate count. There was at least 16 birds and probably more. I will estimate the sex distribution as best I can.
